426. In English we may say-—

a. He gives the boy a book. b. A book is given to the boy. c. The boy is given a book.

Sentences a and b are similarly expressed in Latin, as,—

a. Puero librum dat. b. Liber puero datur.

Observe that the direct object of the active verb becomes the subject of the passive.

Sentence c is foreign to the Latin idiom and cannot be thus expressed. The indirect object of the active cannot be used as

the subject in the passive.
